description:
In 2014, two women from the Netherlands went to Panama seeking a soul-searching trip full of excitement, adventure, and opportunity. But tragedy struck, leaving us with far more questions than answers - particularly involving a camera that turned up with very strange photographs on it.

Chapters:
00:00 Intro
01:37 Documentary Start 
03:56 About Kris & Lisanne
06:00 The Panama Trip
08:03 The Hike
09:33 The Disappearance
12:11 Search Efforts Begin
14:49 The Night Photographs
16:28 Search Efforts Wind Down
17:11 The Backpack is Found
18:10 Remains are found
19:15 Debunking the Rumors
27:35 Image 509
29:53 The Folded Shorts & Pristine Backpack
31:45 Speculation Begins
33:41 Feliciano the Guide
37:17 How Did They Get Lost?
39:00 The Swimming Photo
42:32 Night Photo Theories
48:55 The Remains' Location
49:56 The Guide's Son
53:01 Lost or Foul Play?
55:16 Conclusion

comments.text:
Some people will do anything to convince themselves that foul play was not involved, that everything was normal and that theres a perfectly logical explanation for everything. 
It says more about the person commenting than about the case itself. The parents of the girls are just normal people but the parents of Kris very quickly began to suspect foul play because nothing else added up. 
And then theres the importance of maintaining a good image for tourism. Its not hard to see why the investigation was not as thorough as it should have been. 
We dont know what happened, probably never will, but they just got lost is about the most far-fetched version that I can think of.
The most obvious scenario would somehow involve foul play.  These girls were taking too many risks. South and Central America are statistically dangerous places especially for foreigners and even more so for two young blonde girls. This video works overtime trying to make out that this was just a normal place where such strange things as murder wouldnt happen. This is gang land and there is a very high rate of criminal activities including murder. Murder is not unusual there. The  normalization attempts in this video dont really fit with this part of the world. They apply the concept of what might be normal in a small town in Maine for example.

comments.text:
I think that your video is really interesting, well researched and well argued but in the end I don't believe that they just got lost. Mainly because of the time line and the reports of many witnesses in Boquete. They took their last April 1  photo at just before 14.00 hours. They still had more than four hours daylight in which to get back down to the village and many people confirmed having seen them there at about 15.00- 15.30 hours. The trail is a 4 km there-and-back trip and would take about three to four hours. They went a little further than the Mirador but they could still easily have got back within a couple of hours. Also the path is deeply engraved and veering from it requires a considerable and deliberate effort, as said by the mother of Kris. You'd have to really want to get lost.  
Having said that,  the night photos make it difficult to believe that they were not lost at the time when these were taken but this was one whole week after the girls had set out on the Pianista Trail. It's quite bizarre.

comments.text: In my opinion this is (more or less) what happened: at about 2:30PM the girls reached the 2nd (or actually 3rd as the 2nd is mostly dry) small river (NOT the cable bridge, will explain next where). This river is a bit larger than the one seen in the last day photo with Chris, and offers possibilities of taking a refreshing bath/swim. I think the girls "adventured" down this river to take a swim - that is why they put their bra, sunglasses, phones etc. in the backpack. I don't think they went very far down this river, not at all. I think their plan was to take a short swim and then start walking back to the summit and then back to Boquete. But then something happened (at around 4PM) while they were taking the swim. An accident to one of them? This is very likely. Or an assault? Also not impossible. In either cases I believe that they were not lost, they were not too far from the crossing of the path with this 3rd river. The noise of the river is very loud. I believe that the search teams would not have heard them screaming, especially if they would have walked a bit further off-track along the river. You can see this river and hear the noise here (at min: 9:20):  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O8AI3M1heAY&t=646s This is also the river reached by the girl's parents. The parents say that this river is consistent with the time of the 1st emergency call. In the blog of Romain C (https://imperfectplan.com/2021/11/21/panama-expedition-2021-complete-overview/) you can read more about river #3. The fact that the girls removed their bra and put them in the backpack is very consistent with taking a swim. The fact that the girls did not wear the bra anymore points to the possibility that this was either not possible anymore, or not at all a priority. This is in my opinion an extremely important clue. Something happens while they are taking a swim, probably either naked, or only partially naked. What happened exactly? Why none of them bothered wearing the bra's again? Yet, apparently, they made multiple attempts to call. And Chris's shorts were found, but none of her remains with the shorts. Did she take off the shirts before swimming? Very likely. But why she did not put them on again after the accident?

comments.text:
1. The dog hangs around hikers. It gives the impression the hike is a walk in the park, which it is, if you dont wander off.
2. The girls wanted to be by themselves. Its the mentality of a lot of arrogant tourists or backpackers, they only interact with the locals to a certain limit, they dont want to get too close, and dont want to pay for service.
3. The girls got lost, one got injured, and they probably argued, blaming each other for the situation they got in. The mood was out, no touristy pics. Dont tell me that you never fight with your husband or wife, when you get lost in your car or that you take pictures to document family feuds.
3. They save their phone battery, one of the girls may have placed the backpack, where it had a better chance to be found, which happened eventually. They waited for rescue, thinking it would come in a few hours or days.
4. The search was launched, but too far away from where they were.
5. They took pictures to signal their position to an helicopter.
6. They managed to survive with water, and with an unfaltering hope of getting rescued sooner or later, but died of exhaustion. 
7. The bodies were taken by a flood swell and broken against rocks. Different animals and insects clean the corpses differently.
So, may be the locals are violent people, but accidents happen more often than crime.
